    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-27T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-27T13:00:00-05:00" n="652"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d652">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">840.48 Refugees/7–2744: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-27T20:00:00+02:00"
                            >July 27, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5956. Reference Embassy’s 5811, July 22, 5 p.m., and despatch No. 17024, July
                        24.<note n="38" xml:id="d652fn38">Neither printed.</note> Director IGC has
                    just informed Embassy by letter of discussion with representative of
                    International Red Cross delegation London regarding Horthy offer.<note n="39"
                        xml:id="d652fn39">Adm. Nicholas Horthy, Regent of Hungary; see circular
                        telegram of August 18, <ref target="#pg_1127">p. 1127</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Intercross representative is most anxious that positive response to offer be made
                    as soon as possible since otherwise fears offer will be withdrawn or at least
                    reduced in scope on ground that other countries especially Great Britain and
                    United States are not really interested. Chief delegate IGC strongly urges that
                    American and British Governments decide what they intend to do in response to
                    offer and then make necessary provision for IGC to carry out operations decided
                    upon. IGC most anxious to arrange for places of asylum, transport and
                    maintenance of Jews allowed to leave Hungary and wishes to correlate action with
                    WRB. Please inform WRB. Full text director’s letter being airmailed.<note n="40"
                        xml:id="d652fn40">Despatch 17147, July 28, not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
